<author><name><![CDATA[Cultured_Janner]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-07-04T11:05:16+01:00</updated>
<id>http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=27&amp;p=107#p107</id>
<link href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=27&amp;p=107#p107"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Biggest Anti-Climax]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=27&amp;p=107#p107"><![CDATA[
Out Run definitely should have been much better than it was - nice music on the 128 though, and the multi-loaded levels remained in the memory so you only had to load them once.<br /><br />Knight Rider - nearly two years in development and it was still an unplayable bug-ridden mess. <br /><br />Street Hawk - another big licence, another long wait from Ocean. Although this would have been a fairly decent game if it had been released in early 1985 as originally promised, by the time it actually saw the light of day in late '86, it was very ordinary.<br /><br />Nightshade - after Knight Lore and Alien 8, we were all wondering with lip-smacking anticipation what Ultimate would spring on us next. It was this. Oh dear.<br /><br />Mario Bros - a chance to produce a great Speccy platformer that went begging. Should have been much better.<br /><br />Ghosts 'n' Goblins - good reviews, but I was distinctly underwhelmed. <br /><br />Bionic Commando - I loved the coin-op, and when the Speccy version had great reviews, I bought it and promptly wished I hadn't. Don't know what those reviewers were on, but it must have been good stuff!<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=76">Cultured_Janner</a> — Mon Jul 04, 2011 11:05 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
