<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[Meurglys68]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-07-02T18:21:55+01:00</updated>
<id>http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=27&amp;p=91#p91</id>
<link href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=27&amp;p=91#p91"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Biggest Anti-Climax]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/viewtopic.php?t=27&amp;p=91#p91"><![CDATA[
Difficult one this. I have always been one of those that see Spectrum games as the glass being half-full which meant that I would always try to concentrate on the plus side of any game (even though if I was being honest I did feel disappointed).<br /><br />Anti-Climaxes: <br />Arcadia - I am not sure why but I had convinced myself that I was loading up something that would blow Galaga/Galaxians et al, out of the water. When I finally saw the flickery graphics and flatulence sounding noise of the ship, I was a bit miffed. Still, continued to play it though.<br /><br />Cavelon: For much the same reason as above. However, this game did develop into a favourite. What it lacked in graphics/sound it made up for in gameplay. Still play the game.<br /><br />The Hobbit: Now I know that this was a ground breaking text adventure (or piece of interactive fiction, if you prefer), but it annoyed the crap out of me. Being a huge fan of Tolkien and having just finished Lord of the Rings for the first time a few months before the game was released, I was mortified when I saw the game. My dreams of taking on Smaug withered exponentially with every 'you can't do that' or 'I don't understand'.  In hindsight my expectations far exceeded what the Spectrum was capable of.<br /><br />All if which leads me to realise that none of the above constitute a 'biggest anti-climax' - I shall need to go away and ponder this more.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=77">Meurglys68</a> — Sat Jul 02, 2011 6:21 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
